# Coding Standards

## Import Organization

Always place all imports at the top of the file. Never place imports in the middle of the file or inside functions.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import express from "express";
import cors from "cors";
import { Router } from "express";

const app = express();

// ❌ BAD
const app = express();

import cors from "cors"; // Don't import in the middle

function myFunction() {
  import { Router } from "express"; // Don't import inside functions
}
```

## Comments

Keep comments minimal. Write self-documenting code with clear variable and function names.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Clear code, minimal comments
export const createStore = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const { name, type = "WOOCOMMERCE" } = req.body;
  
  if (!name) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "Store name is required" });
  }
  
  // Business logic here
};

// ❌ BAD - Too many comments
export const createStore = async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  // Get name from request body
  const { name, type = "WOOCOMMERCE" } = req.body;
  
  // Check if name exists
  if (!name) {
    // Return error if no name
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "Store name is required" });
  }
  
  // Do the business logic
};
```

## Documentation Files

Do not create summary or documentation markdown files unless explicitly requested. Focus on writing clean, readable code instead.
